Product description

Protect online accounts against unauthorized access. * Works with Google, Facebook, Dropbox, Twitter, LastPass, Dashlane, and hundreds of other services. * Durable, waterproof, and crush resistant * Multi-protocol support: FIDO2, Yubico OTP, OATH-TOTP, OATH-HOTP, Smart card (PIV), OpenPGP, Challenge-Response. * Interface: USB-A * Made in the USA & Sweden * Always keep a spare key as backup *

    The FIDO certification adds an extra layer of credibility, assuring users of its compatibility with a wide range of platforms and services. The Nano's compact size is a standout feature, allowing it to seamlessly blend into my device without protruding or being cumbersome.

    Setting up the YubiKey 5 Nano was a breeze, and the connectivity via USB-A ensures widespread compatibility across various devices. The robust construction instills confidence in its durability, and the convenience of having this tiny security powerhouse on my keychain is unmatched.

    I appreciate the simplicity and effectiveness of the YubiKey 5 Nano – it truly streamlines the authentication process without sacrificing security. For anyone serious about protecting their online accounts from unauthorized access, this is an investment that pays dividends in digital peace of mind.     Skyelle
    5.0 out of 5 stars Does the job and is discreet
    Reviewed in Canada on 12 June 2022
    Verified Purchase
    I was told I needed to use 2FA (or MFA) for work, but I don't own a smart phone. Someone recommended the Yubikey series. I wanted an option that I can leave in my computer, but the larger keys stick out of the USB slot quite a bit and I was afraid I would accidentally knock it off. I chose the nano because it barely sticks out of the USB slot and you hardly notice it's there, unless you're looking for it. The security function works perfectly and was fairly easy to set up. I just touch the top of it to authenticate. Because it has such a small profile, it can be difficult to remove from the port, but I'm not taking any points off for that because I like that it's small and discreet. Just keep a thin nylon string or unwaxed dental floss nearby, so you can thread the hole to pull it out, when you have to. I also have a backup key that I set up at the same time, just in case. The nano is expensive, but cheaper and less intrusive than a smart phone!
